🛠️ Using gh pr checkout

The gh pr checkout command is the simplest way to check out a pull request locally . It automatically handles fetching the correct branch and switching to it.

Basic Command and Options

```bash
gh pr checkout 214
```

This will create a local branch with the same name as the pull request's head branch and switch to it .

You can customize this behavior with a few useful flags :

· -b, --branch <string>: Check out the PR into a new branch with a custom name.
  ```bash
  gh pr checkout 214 --branch my-review-branch
  ```
· --detach: Check out the PR in a "detached HEAD" state without creating a new branch .
  ```bash
  gh pr checkout 214 --detach
  ```
· -f, --force: Reset the existing local branch to the latest state of the pull request, useful if the PR has been updated .

🔍 If You Encounter Issues

If the command fails, here are the most common prerequisites and solutions:

1. Install and Authenticate GitHub CLI: Ensure the GitHub CLI (gh) is installed and you're logged in with gh auth login. You also need push access to the target repository or for the PR author to have allowed maintainer edits .
2. Check Your Repository: The command must be run from within the Git repository that the pull request targets.
3. Alternative Selectors: Besides the PR number, you can also use the PR's URL or the name of the branch associated with the PR :
   ```bash
   gh pr checkout https://github.com/owner/repo/pull/214
   gh pr checkout feature-branch-name
   ```

🗂️ Alternative Git Methods

If you cannot use the GitHub CLI, you can use direct Git commands. Fetch the PR and create a branch for it manually :

```bash
git fetch origin pull/214/head:pr-214
git checkout pr-214
```

